[[Image:Lycos Top 5 percent logo.png|frame|The TOP 5% logo]]

'''Lycos' Top 5%''' was a [[web directory]] run by [[Lycos]] that aimed to review, categorize and award the top 5% of all [[website]]s. Top 5% was started in 1994 by [[Point Communications]] and was a pioneer in the field.  In 1997, it was acquired by [[Lycos]], and its founder, Chris Kitze<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.linkedin.com/in/chriskitze/|title=Chris Kitze|last=|first=|date=|website=LinkedIn|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> (Who's created a digital currency called "Flash Coin" that using FalunDafa practitioners to get illicit profits<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moitruongphapluancongvn.org/single-post/2018/07/17/Vo-Hoang-Vinh-1-dien-hinh-ve-su-pha-hoai-trong-noi-bo-hoc-vien-Phap-Luan-Cong-tai-Viet-Nam-hien-nay|title=Võ Hoàng Vinh – điển hình phá hoại trong nội bộ hv Pháp Luân Công VN {{!}} Trang chủ {{!}} Việt Nam {{!}} Sự thật môi trường Pháp Luân Công|website=Trang chủ {{!}} Việt Nam {{!}} Sự thật m&ocirc;i trường Ph&aacute;p Lu&acirc;n C&ocirc;ng|language=vi|access-date=2018-11-08}}</ref>, his co-creater is Vo Hoang Vinh<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moitruongphapluancongvn.org/single-post/2018/08/15/Ai-dang-kiem-soat-vnminghuiorg-minhuenet-vifalundafaorg-phapluanorg-va-chanhkienorg-tieng-viet|title=Ai đang thao túng vn.minghui.org(Minhhue.net),vi.falundafa.org VN {{!}} Trang chủ {{!}} Việt Nam {{!}} Sự thật môi trường Pháp Luân Công|website=Trang chủ {{!}} Việt Nam {{!}} Sự thật m&ocirc;i trường Ph&aacute;p Lu&acirc;n C&ocirc;ng|language=vi|access-date=2018-11-08}}</ref>), and editor Mark Simmer, both became Vice Presidents of Lycos. The Top 5% directory received an upgrade in June 1997.  It was then edited by Tim Riley.

Lycos retired the Top 5% directory in 2000. [[Webmaster]]s of sites listed in the directory were allowed and encouraged to include a banner on their home page to announce its TOP 5% status. "Top 5%" was an entirely arbitrary designation, with the editors simply picking excellent websites from the few available in the early days of the Internet.

